  "output": "## Avelo Performance Analysis\n\nI read the actual source for each area you asked about (not just relying on notes from earlier sessions today) and verified line numbers against current code. One framing note: this is a Swift/SwiftUI macOS app using the `@Observable` macro, not React тАФ I've translated \"unnecessary re-renders\" to the SwiftUI equivalent (redundant computed-property work triggered on every view body evaluation).\n\n### 1. N+1 Query Patterns\n\n**A. `VoucherService.loadAccounts` тАФ per-account lookup in GST round-off normalization**\n`Avelo/Core/Services/VoucherService.swift:1164-1175`\n```swift\nprivate func loadAccounts(ids: Set<Account.ID>, accountRepo: AccountRepository) throws -> [Account.ID: Account] {\n    var out: [Account.ID: Account] = [:]\n    for id in ids {\n        guard let account = try accountRepo.findById(id) else { throw AppError.notFound(\"Account\") }\n        out[id] = account\n    }\n    return out\n}\n```\nRuns on every voucher post/edit for sales/purchase/credit-note/debit-note types. Fix: add a batch fetch to `AccountRepository`:\n```swift\nfunc findByIds(_ ids: Set<Account.ID>) throws -> [Account] {\n    guard !ids.isEmpty else { return [] }\n    let placeholders = Array(repeating: \"?\", count: ids.count).joined(separator: \",\")\n    return try db.query(\"SELECT * FROM avelo_accounts WHERE id IN (\\(placeholders))\",\n                         bind: ids.map { .text($0.uuidString) }) { try Account(row: $0) }\n}\n```\nthen `Dictionary(uniqueKeysWithValues: try accountRepo.findByIds(ids).map { ($0.id, $0) })`.\n\n**B. `BOMService.validateBOMInput` тАФ per-component item lookup**\n`Avelo/Core/Services/BOMService.swift:75-87`\n```swift\nfor component in components {\n    ...\n    guard let item = try InventoryRepository(db: db).findItem(id: component.componentItemId), ... \n}\n```\nA BOM with 50 components does 50 separate queries (plus 50 `InventoryRepository` allocations). Fix: fetch all component items once with an `IN` query before the loop, look up from a dictionary.\n\n**C. `InvoicePDFService` тАФ stock rows loop**\n`Avelo/Core/Services/InvoicePDFService.swift:47-57`\n```swift\nlet movements = try inventoryRepo.listMovements(forVoucher: voucherId)\nlet stockRows = try movements.map { movement in\n    let item = try inventoryRepo.findItemById(movement.itemId)   // N+1\n    ...\n}\n```\nFix: collect `Set(movements.map(\\.itemId))`, batch-fetch, then map from a dictionary.\n\n**D. `DashboardViewModel.reload` тАФ per-bank-account and per-month report queries**\n`Avelo/Features/Dashboard/DashboardViewModel.swift:55-62` and `:87-103`\n```swift\nfor bankAccount in accounts where bankAccount.isBankAccount {\n    let ledger = try report.ledger(accountId: bankAccount.id, financialYearId: fyId)  // 1 query per bank account\n}\n...\nwhile cursor <= reportEndDate {\n    let l = try report.ledger(...)                 // 1 query per month\n    let exp = try report.profitAndLoss(...)         // 1 query per month\n    ...\n}\n```\nThis is the dashboard's landing screen, so it runs on every app launch/company switch. A 12-month FY with 5 bank accounts = ~29 separate report queries. `ReportService`'s cache doesn't help here since each call has a distinct date range. Fix: add a single grouped-by-account or grouped-by-month aggregation query in `ReportRepository` (e.g. `monthlyTotals(accountCode:, fyId:) -> [MonthlyTotal]` in one SQL `GROUP BY strftime('%Y-%m', date)`), replacing the loop.\n\n**E. `AccountTreeCache.reload` тАФ opening balance override per ledger**\n`Avelo/Core/Cache/AccountTreeCache.swift:58-67`\n```swift\nlet openingOverrides = try Dictionary(uniqueKeysWithValues: ledgers.map { ledger in\n    (ledger.id, try reportRepository.signedOpeningBalance(for: ledger, filter: filter, openingContext: openingContext))\n})\n```\nEvery ledger triggers its own `signedOpeningBalance` call. For a chart of accounts with hundreds of ledgers this is hundreds of small queries on every tree rebuild (invalidated on every posted voucher). Note the `loadLedgerBalances` function directly below it (lines 106-159) already does this correctly тАФ batches ledgers into chunks of 500 and issues one `IN`-clause query per chunk. The opening-balance path should follow the same pattern instead of looping per-ledger.\n\n### 2. Algorithmic Inefficiency (not strictly N+1, but same symptom)\n\n**`BankReconciliationService.reconcile`**\n`Avelo/Core/Services/BankReconciliationService.swift:96-119`\n```swift\nfor s in statement {\n    if let v = vouchers.first(where: { v in ... }) { ... }   // O(statement ├Ч vouchers)\n}\n```\nQuadratic in statement-line count ├Ч candidate-voucher count. Fine for a small manual reconciliation, but a large monthly bank statement import (thousands of lines) against thousands of open vouchers will visibly stall. Fix: bucket `vouchers` by date (or by `amountPaise`) into a dictionary before the loop, so each statement line only scans candidates within its date-tolerance window rather than the entire voucher set.\n\n### 3. Redundant Computation (SwiftUI's analog to \"unnecessary re-renders\")\n\n**`VoucherEditViewModel.isBalanced`**\n`Avelo/Features/Vouchers/VoucherEditViewModel.swift:244-258`\n```swift\npublic var totalDebitPaise: Int64 {\n    (try? CheckedMath.sum(lines.lazy.filter { $0.side == .debit }.map { Currency.parseRupeeInput($0.amount) ?? 0 }, ...)) ?? 0\n}\npublic var totalCreditPaise: Int64 {\n    (try? CheckedMath.sum(lines.lazy.filter { $0.side == .credit }.map { Currency.parseRupeeInput($0.amount) ?? 0 }, ...)) ?? 0\n}\npublic var isBalanced: Bool { totalDebitPaise == totalCreditPaise && totalDebitPaise > 0 }\n```\n`isBalanced` is read from the voucher grid view body, so it re-parses every line's amount string (via `Currency.parseRupeeInput`, a string-parsing call) twice тАФ once for debit, once for credit тАФ on every access. With `@Observable` tracking `lines` at the array level, any keystroke in any line triggers a full re-scan of all lines, twice. Fix: compute both totals in a single pass:\n```swift\nprivate var totals: (debit: Int64, credit: Int64) {\n    var debit: Int64 = 0, credit: Int64 = 0\n    for line in lines {\n        let amount = Currency.parseRupeeInput(line.amount) ?? 0\n        if line.side == .debit { debit += amount } else { credit += amount }\n    }\n    return (debit, credit)\n}\npublic var totalDebitPaise: Int64 { totals.debit }\npublic var totalCreditPaise: Int64 { totals.credit }\npublic var isBalanced: Bool { let t = totals; return t.debit == t.credit && t.debit > 0 }\n```\n(Still recomputes on each access, but halves the per-access work тАФ one pass instead of two, one parse per line instead of two.)\n\n### 4. Caching тАФ what's already good, and the gap\n\n`ReportService` (`Avelo/Core/Services/ReportService.swift:8, 116-150`) has a solid changeToken-invalidated cache (LRU-capped at 128 entries, keyed by report type + filter params) shared across `ledger`/`trialBalance`/`profitAndLoss`/`balanceSheet` calls, and `VoucherService` correctly calls `ReportService.invalidateCache` after every mutating operation (post/edit/reverse/cancel/bounce/represent тАФ checked all 7 call sites). No gap there.\n\nThe gap is **`gstSummary`, `outstanding`, `stockValuation`, `dayBook`, `cashFlow`, `stockAgeing`** (`ReportService.swift:81-109`) тАФ these bypass the cache entirely and hit `repository` directly every call. `DashboardViewModel.reload` calls `outstanding` (├Ч2) and `stockValuation` on every dashboard load with no caching, unlike the ledger/trialBalance calls right next to them in the same function. Fix: route these through the same `Self.cache.value`/`Self.cache.store` pattern used by `ledger`.\n\n### 5. Memory Leaks\n\nChecked `Task` lifecycle (autosave in `VoucherEditViewModel`, `AccountTreeCache.reload`, all feature ViewModels' `Task.detached` reload pattern), `NSEvent` monitors (`KeyboardMonitor` тАФ weak-captured), and delegate references (`Router` тАФ weak). Found none. No `NotificationCenter` or `Timer` observers exist in the codebase at all, which removes the two most common leak sources in SwiftUI/AppKit apps by construction. This is clean.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order if you want to act on these**: D (dashboard N+1, hit on every launch) and E (AccountTreeCache opening balances, hit on every posted voucher) are the highest-frequency, highest-impact fixes. F (bank reconciliation) only matters at statement-import scale. A/B/C are lower-frequency but easy, mechanical fixes. G is cheap and localized.\n",
